<topicdoc>
<name> ReninSecretion - Overview </name>
<label> Overview </label>
<content>

In the adult kidney, renin is synthesized by juxtaglomerular
epitheloid cells that are located in the media of the renal 
afferent arterioles just adjacent to the glomerulus. The 
transcription rate of the renin gene is considered as the 
essential event that determines the renin production rate.
The renin gene transcript gives rise to preprorenin protein,
which is cleaved into prorenin in the endoplasmic reticulum. 
Prorenin is is sorted into two different pathways at the 
level of the Golgi apparatus. Prorenin is either exported 
to small clear vesicles which are immediately secreted by
the constitutive pathway, or it is glycosylated and stored 
in dense secretory granules for regulated exocytosis. In 
the dense secretory granules, an acidic intracellular pH
creates an optimal environment for protease activity which
activates prorenin to renin. Renin remains stored in the 
vesicles awaiting controlled release. At the cellular level,
renin secretion appears to be oppositely controlled by
cyclic AMP and by calcium signalling pathways. Any maneuver
that increases cyclic AMP strongly stimulates renin secretion. 
In contrast, increases in cytosolic calcium concentration
potently inhibits renin release. 
  
Park CS, Malvin RL, Murray RD, Cho KW. Renin secretion
as a function of renal renin content in dogs.
Am J Physiol 234: F506 - F509, 1978.

Galen FX, Devaux C, Houot AM, Corvol P, Corvol MT,
Gubler MC, Mounier F, Camilleeri JP. Renin biosynthesis
by human tumoral juxtaglomerular cells. Evidences for
a renin precursor. J Clin Invest 73: 1144 - 1155, 1984.

Kurtz A. Control of renin synthesis and secretion.
Am J Hypertension January 2012.

